:INFO
Leather Belt Tools Worth Owning
You can start with a minimal kit. These are the tools that matter most and what to spend money on versus what to substitute.

:CHECKLIST
Must-Have Tools
[ ] Strap cutter — consistent width every time; buy before you have regrets
[ ] Edge beveler size 2 — the most used size for belts
[ ] Overstitch wheel — marks stitch spacing evenly before pricking
[ ] Stitching chisels (2-prong and 4-prong set) — cleaner holes than an awl
[ ] 2 curved harness needles — #1 or #2 size
[ ] Poly board or marble slab for cutting on

:CHECKLIST
Useful but Substitutable
[ ] Wing divider — for marking a consistent stitch line; a ruler works
[ ] Beeswax block — for waxing thread; birthday candle works in a pinch
[ ] Slicker burnishing tool — a hardwood dowel works
[ ] Maul or mallet — for striking chisels cleanly

:NOTE
Invest in Chisels, Not an Awl
A stitching awl produces inconsistent holes that make a belt look hand-made in the bad sense. A set of stitching chisels (pricking irons) with consistent spacing produces even, angled holes that give a professional result. Buy one 2-prong and one 4-prong in your preferred pitch (3mm or 4mm spacing) and use them together.

:PATH
Where to Buy Leather Supplies
Tandy Leather and Springfield Leather carry the full range of hand tools.
|
:INFO
Where to Buy Leather Supplies
Tandy Leather has physical locations in the US and carries all essential tools. Springfield Leather Company has a broader online selection with better prices on bulk leather. Rocky Mountain Leather carries premium tools and Japanese leather hardware. For leather itself, buy a shoulder or bend — denser grain, better for belts than the belly portion of a hide.
